    "title": "The Feynman Technique: Learn Anything by Teaching It to a Five-Year-Old",
    "category": "Learning Strategies",
    "author": "Learn & Grow Team",
    "readTime": "6 min read",
    "excerpt": "Nobel-winning physicist Richard Feynman had a simple test for whether he truly understood something: could he explain it simply? Here's how to use his method for any subject.",
    "content": "Richard Feynman won a Nobel Prize in physics, but he's remembered almost as much for how he learned as for what he discovered. Feynman believed that true understanding of a concept could be measured by one simple test: could you explain it in plain language, without jargon, to someone with no background in the subject \u2014 say, a curious child? If you couldn't, that gap in your explanation revealed exactly where your own understanding was actually shaky, no matter how confident you felt while simply reading about the topic.\n\nThis idea evolved into what's now called the Feynman Technique, a four-step method that has become one of the most respected learning strategies precisely because it targets a problem every student runs into: the illusion of understanding. It's entirely possible to read a chapter, nod along with a lecture, and feel like you've grasped a concept, only to discover during an exam that you actually can't apply or explain it. The Feynman Technique catches this gap before the exam does.\n\nThe first step is choosing a concept and writing its name at the top of a blank page. This could be anything from a specific idea in a lecture \u2014 say, supply and demand elasticity, or cellular respiration \u2014 to a broader topic you're trying to master for an upcoming test.\n\nThe second step is the core of the technique: explain the concept in your own words, as if teaching it to someone who has never encountered it before \u2014 literally imagine explaining it to a twelve-year-old. This means no jargon, no borrowed textbook phrasing, and no vague hand-waving over the hard parts. You have to actually work through the logic yourself, in language simple enough that a non-expert could follow it. Write this explanation out, don't just think it through in your head \u2014 the act of writing forces a level of precision that mental rehearsal alone doesn't.\n\nThe third step is where the real value emerges: identify the gaps. As you write your simple explanation, you will almost certainly hit points where you get stuck, where your explanation becomes vague, or where you catch yourself reaching for a technical term because you don't actually know how to explain the underlying idea in plain language. These gaps are not a sign of failure \u2014 they are the entire point of the exercise. They tell you precisely which parts of the concept you don't yet understand, information that simply rereading your notes would never have revealed to you.\n\nThe fourth step is going back to your source material \u2014 textbook, lecture notes, professor's office hours \u2014 specifically to fill those identified gaps, rather than rereading the material in general. This makes your review dramatically more efficient, because you're not spending time reviewing things you already understand; you're targeting exactly the parts that were unclear.\n\nOnce you've filled the gaps, repeat the explanation from the beginning, ideally simplifying it even further and cutting out any remaining jargon or overly complex phrasing. Feynman himself would iterate this process multiple times on genuinely difficult concepts, refining his explanation until it was as simple and clear as the concept could honestly be made \u2014 some ideas are inherently complex and can't be reduced infinitely, but most concepts taught in introductory university courses can be explained more simply than textbooks usually manage.\n\nThe technique works particularly well as a study method with a real study partner, if you can find one. Explaining a concept out loud to a friend, and having them ask genuine clarifying questions when something doesn't make sense, replicates the gap-finding function of the writing exercise but with the added benefit of another person's perspective on where your explanation breaks down. If no study partner is available, explaining out loud to an empty room, a pet, or even a recording works almost as well \u2014 the value comes from vocalizing your understanding, not from having an actual audience.\n\nOne particularly useful application of the Feynman Technique is for concepts you're tempted to just memorize without truly understanding \u2014 mathematical formulas, chemical processes, historical cause-and-effect chains. Memorization without understanding is brittle; it collapses the moment an exam question asks you to apply the concept in an unfamiliar way rather than simply recite it. Being able to explain why a formula works, not just what the formula is, gives you the flexibility to apply it to novel problems, which is almost always what university exams are actually testing.\n\nThe technique also doubles as an excellent diagnostic for exam preparation. A useful pre-exam ritual is to go through your course's major topics and, for each one, attempt a one-minute Feynman-style explanation without notes. Any topic where you stumble, hesitate, or reach for jargon you can't unpack is a topic that needs more study time before the exam \u2014 a far more accurate signal than simply feeling like you've 'covered' the material during a study session.\n\nWhat makes the Feynman Technique so durable as a learning strategy, used across disciplines from physics to law to medicine, is that it doesn't rely on any special resources or tools. It requires only a blank page, some honesty with yourself about where your explanation gets shaky, and the willingness to go back and actually fill those gaps rather than glossing over them. The next time you finish reading a chapter and feel like you understand it, test that feeling \u2014 try explaining it simply, out loud or on paper, and see what gaps appear.",
    "tags": [
      "feynman technique",
      "learning strategies",
      "study techniques",
      "understanding",
      "exam preparation"
    ],
